es asthma-induced reprogramming to enhance therapeutic specificity. Despite its importance and opening a new era of a new type of immunotherapy- organ-induced prevention-, experimental data on the complex network of asthma-T cells-microglia-tumor and inter-and intra-cellular signaling within those key immune cells is sparse. Thus, computational studies on the over-immune effects of these interactions on brain cancer risk , and on the sensitivity of the model predictions to key intracellular parameters may provide important insights to guide and create new experiments aimed at the development of new, innovative therapeutic strategies. 21 , 58 The proposed framework may generalize to other tumor-immune interactions beyond NF1-associated optic glioma. For instance, while mice with hyperglycemia may promote the growth of gliomas via RAGE expression and inhibition of immune responses, suppression of pro-inflammatory cytokines was shown to inhibit glioma subtypes in diabetic mice. There exist conflicting epidemiological studies on positive  and negative 63 – 68  effects of diabetes on cancer development in glioma patients 69 – 72 . Alzheimer’s disease was also shown to have negative correlation with GBM development via signaling pathways such as PI3K/Akt/mTOR axis 73 . The mathematical framework in this work can be applied to identify the key signaling network with a similar inhibition mechanism and to develop new enhanced therapeutic approaches to preventing cancer. 74 – 76 In this work, we did not take into account many microenvironmental factors, such as the midkine signaling pathway on the optic nerve , the effect of caffeic acid phenethyl ester on dampening microglia 77 , 78 , the multifaceted role of decorin-controlled IFN 21 γ  in asthma and cancer , the role of decorin in the regulation of receptor tyrosine kinase (IGFR1, c-MET, EGFR) on other cells 79 – 83  that may play critical roles in progression, invasion, and growth of gliomas, and the development of anti-cancer drugs. For instance, decorin was shown to inhibit the invasive capacity of GBM cells in the brain 84 – 86 . While decorin-induced IFN 42 γ  activity  plays an important role in maintaining lung tissue inflammation in asthma 79 , 80 , decorin enhances anti-oncogenic activities such as suppressing angiogenesis and metastatic potential in cancer progression 87 . However, the mathematical model in this work can serve as a first step toward further experimental design and more detailed modeling, such as hybrid multi-scale models 81 – 83  by incorporating these brain tumor microenvironmental factors. It is also possible that other immune systemic diseases involving T lymphocytes, such as diabetes 87 – 98 , eczema 73 , 99 , rheumatoid arthritis 53 , 100 , 101 , may also affect glioma development via a similar set of complex mechanisms. For instance, a group of studies 102 , 103  showed the inverse association of diabetes with glioma, while other groups showed contradictory or nonlinear results 99 . Further analysis and investigation of this correlation at the molecular biology level is necessary. 70 , 73 , 104 , 105 While the present model provides quantitative insights into the mechanistic link between asthma-associated immune signaling and optic glioma progression, it is formulated under a simple assumption of the well-mixed system without explicit spatial representation. However, cytokine diffusion and immune-cell migration play a significant role in regulation of tumor growth , tumor suppression 91 , 106 , angiogenesis 107 – 110 , necrosis 111 , 112 , recurrence of tumor in the other hemisphere 113 , 114 , and delivery of the therapeutic agents through BBB 115 , 116  in spatially heterogeneous microenvironments. In particular, it is important to understand the heterogeneity in cell compositions and roles in two distinct organs, the lung—where asthma-related T cell reprogramming originates—and the brain, where an optic glioma develops. In order to develop a new optimal treatment method for the optic glioma, we plan to investigate these spatial aspects in future work. The model in this work provides a basic platform to better understand the spatio-temporal dynamics of the complete, asthma-optic glioma interactions and drug delivery. 117 – 119
